    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Describe your issue\n\nWe have a known issue when calling `cdef void nogil` functions that can raise exceptions because it always requires us to reacquire the GIL to check if any exception is raised.\n\nI think we can usually avoid that though.\n\nIf `CYTHON_THREAD_LOCAL` is available then we can have the function write to a (C/C++) thread local flag to indicate that it's set an exception (which is effectively just what the Python exception state is). That should be a cheap check compared to re-acquiring the GIL.\n\nWe could easily do that by default for internal Cython-defined cdef functions. For `cdef extern from` functions we wouldn't be able to do that.  For `cimport`ed functions we couldn't do that immediately (because they might come from older Cython versions) but eventually we'd be able to assume that.\n\nMy feeling is that this would probably want a new exception specification to indicate it rather than trying to bolt this onto `except *`, but both would work.",
    "closed_at": null,
